Adam provided an overview of the current allocation process at Citi Trends:

- The process starts with the financial chain plan in Island Pacific, which leads to the unit plan and the climate module where the actual allocation is done.
- The stores are divided into three weather zones - warm, middle, and cold. The product distribution is planned at the department level for each store, considering historical sales performance.
- The final allocation plan is created by combining the store-level department plan with the climate class plan, resulting in a store-level class-based plan for sales, inventory, and open-to-buy.
- The allocation analysts use this plan to guide their product allocation decisions, considering factors like historical sales, product characteristics, and strategic initiatives.
- The plans are created quarterly with a nine-month rolling module, and the team reviews the plans to ensure they make sense at a macro, strategic level.

## Problem Statement / Business Requirement

- We will develop one solution for several scenarios:

1. Crossdock OrdersPO Level Attribute
2. Matched Store BuysProduct Level Attribute
3. Coordinate GroupsMultiple SKUs that are part of a coordinated outfit, for example, a matching top and bottom, must have each SKU attributed with the same coordinate group code. The best way to use this information will be to capture like coordinate group codes within the DFU and group the SKUs together for distribution.

### Crossdock Orders

Citi Trends requires the ability to allocate predefined allocation quantities for POs flagged as Crossdock orders

metadata.title: The Crossdock Problem / Matched Store Buys

content:
equires the ability to allocate predefined allocation quantities for POs flagged as Crossdock orders

- ~4.7% of share from daily POs.
- Data shows that, most of the crossdock POs consist only single dfu but ~17% of those can consist multiple dfuâ€™s.
- Predefined allocation quantities are embedded in PO comments determined in MDLs (min distribution lots), e.g. one SKU on the PO could have an MDL of 6, and the other an MDL of 10, and we are required to allocate one MDL of each to the relevant storesAssumption: PO quantity can be used to determine the ratio
- There will be an attribute at the PO header level used to identify Crossdock orders, dc_options == "CROSSDOCK".

# KPI Metric & Calculation Details

- KPI metric is determined as weighted in stock.
- Metric calculation is based on DFU Store level.

## 1. Weight Calculation

- Weights per DFU/Store is calculated dynamically (new weight for every date)
- Weight calculation considers climate info from store master data and referred as region in the prototype excel.
- From DFU level, we calculate DFU-region total demand.
- From store level, we calculate department-region & department-store total demand.using those, calculate store_index = department-store / department-region
- Based on those calculate weights as;Weight = (DFU-region demand) * (store_index)
- Weight calculation explanation prototype excel. In the prototype excel, demand is based on average of last 4 weeks of sales, but afterwards by Citiâ€™s request, it changed. Now we are calculating weights using last 2 weeks + next 2 weeks.

> Note: For the most current dates (in which next 2 weeks is not available yet) we only use available dates. Therefore, weight calculation may slightly change with addition of new days when we are updating the report.

## 2. In Stock Threshold

- For in stock calculation, we do not use 0/1 logic (if inventory > 0, in stock rate 100%). Instead, we are using active SKU count of DFUs to determine their threshold.
- For this, active SKU counts are calculated dynamically (per date).Rule of activeness is, for a specific date, if there is any inventory or sales record in the last 28 days of that SKU at the chain level, it is flagged as active.
- Using this, in stock rate is determined in DFU / Store level.

The *Forecast Accuracy Report* provides a consolidated view of how well sales forecasts align with actual performance. It enables users to evaluate forecast accuracy at multiple business levels (concept, division, department, store, brand, DFU) and drill down to the most granular DFUâ€“storeâ€“week data. The report highlights key error metrics such as Bias and wMAPE to track performance, identify improvement areas, and support decision-making.

The report includes only LLTD forecasts. Results are shown for DFUâ€“store pairs where an LLTD forecast was generated for that week.

- Total Sales = actual sales for those DFUâ€“store pairs with an LLTD forecast.
- Total Prediction = forecasted sales for DFUâ€“store pairs that had at least one day of actual sales available in that week.
